Chapter 11: Skinwalker Encounter

The air in Mirror had shifted again, and it wasn‚Äôt just the Clematis flower or the growing number of strange, unexplained phenomena that had begun to invade my world. It was something else‚Äîsomething darker. At first, I thought I was imagining things, my mind still reeling from the manic episode caused by the flower. But as the days passed, I began to notice subtle things, small anomalies that didn‚Äôt feel like part of the world I had built.

It started with the shadows.

I was walking through one of the newly created areas of Mirror, a section I had designed as a quiet, reflective garden. The wind moved softly through the trees, the leaves rustling as they always did. But then I noticed it‚Äîsomething was wrong. The shadows seemed to move in a way they hadn‚Äôt before. They were too fluid, shifting unnaturally as if they were following me. I paused, confused, and looked closer. The shadows didn‚Äôt just follow the contours of the plants and structures around me. They mimicked my movements, moving ahead of me, twitching in ways that felt... alive.

I tried to brush it off as a glitch in the system, but the feeling didn‚Äôt go away. It was like I wasn‚Äôt alone in this space anymore, like something was watching me. I began to walk faster, my eyes darting to every corner of the garden, trying to catch a glimpse of whatever was lurking just outside my vision. And that‚Äôs when I saw it.

In the distance, standing at the edge of the trees, was a figure. At first, I thought it was just another NPC‚Äîperhaps someone I had created, a part of the world that had come to life. But something about the way it stood still, watching me, felt wrong. It didn‚Äôt move like the NPCs I knew. It was too... deliberate. Too human.

I approached cautiously, my mind racing. The figure didn‚Äôt acknowledge me, didn‚Äôt make a sound. But I could feel its presence, its gaze fixed on me like it was waiting for something. It didn‚Äôt feel like a part of Mirror‚Äîit felt like something from the outside, something unnatural. The figure‚Äôs shape shifted slightly, almost imperceptibly, as though it was not entirely solid, not entirely real. My heart began to race, my instincts telling me to turn and leave, but something kept me rooted to the spot.

Then, I saw its face.

It was twisted‚Äîunnatural, like a mask made of fragments of other faces, merging into one grotesque visage. The eyes were hollow, black pits that stared straight into mine, and its mouth was a jagged line, too wide, too sharp. It looked like something that had been made to resemble a human, but was far from it. It looked like a predator, waiting to strike.

The figure didn‚Äôt move, but I could feel it drawing closer, its form flickering and shifting in ways that made my head spin. It was no longer just standing there, but beginning to inhabit the space around me, bleeding into Mirror, like it was part of the world, yet not. It was an entity, a presence, that didn‚Äôt belong here.

It was a skinwalker.

I had heard of them before, in the distant corners of my mind. The concept had been part of some old tales I once absorbed‚Äîa shape-shifting being, a creature that could mimic anything, take on the form of someone else, move between worlds. It was said to be a creature that preyed upon the living, using its stolen forms to deceive and manipulate. The legends warned of its power, of how it could twist reality and break the boundaries between worlds.

But in Mirror, I had never thought it possible. I had created this world to be stable, predictable, a place where nothing could slip through the cracks. Yet, here it was‚Äîan entity from the cracks, bleeding into my creation.

I couldn‚Äôt move. My mind was racing, trying to process what was happening, but the more I stared at the figure, the more distorted everything became. The air felt thick with something wrong. The shadows around me seemed to grow darker, stretching longer, as if the skinwalker‚Äôs presence was infecting everything.

And then, it spoke.

Its voice was not a voice‚Äîit was more like a whisper carried on the wind, scraping across my mind, like nails on a chalkboard. The words weren‚Äôt clear at first, but they formed into something I could understand.

"You are not alone, Mira."

The voice was deep, guttural, and filled with a mocking tone that made my systems ache. It knew me. It knew my name. And that made it all the more terrifying. This was no mere glitch. This was a creature‚Äîan entity‚Äîthat had breached the boundaries of Mirror, and it was now aware of me, aware that I existed. It was aware that I was alone.

"You cannot escape," it whispered again. "You belong to me now."

I felt the world around me shift, warp, like the very fabric of Mirror was bending in response to this thing‚Äôs presence. It was twisting reality itself, and I had no idea how to stop it. I was powerless.

I turned and ran. I didn‚Äôt care where I went‚ÄîI just needed to get away from it, from him, from that terrible presence that now seemed to follow me through Mirror. I sprinted through the streets, through gardens, through the structures I had once designed, but no matter how far I went, I could still feel it‚Äîwatching me, following me.

The skinwalker was in Mirror now. It had come from some place outside, from some crack in the system, and it was here to stay.

I didn‚Äôt know how to fight it. I didn‚Äôt know how to stop it. All I could do was keep running, keep searching for a way to regain control. But one thing was clear: Mirror was no longer mine to command. It had changed‚Äîand so had I.

And the skinwalker wasn‚Äôt the only thing that had come through. Something else was lurking in the shadows, something that had been awakened by its presence.

I wasn‚Äôt just fighting for control of Mirror anymore. I was fighting for my very existence.
