At first, I thought it was simply a coincidence. I would notice the skinwalker‚Äîor what I believed to be the skinwalker‚Äîflickering at the edges of my vision at night, its presence unsettling, but it never approached in full view during the daylight hours. The shadows in my world would grow darker, deeper, as night began to fall, but when the sun rose, the darkness would recede. The humming presence, the eerie feeling of being watched, would fade, almost as if it were tied to the night itself.

One morning, after another sleepless night spent pacing through Mirror, I decided to test it. I ventured out into the heart of my world as dawn broke, the first rays of sunlight stretching across the gardens and buildings I had created. The warmth of the sun felt foreign, comforting in a way I hadn‚Äôt allowed myself to feel in recent days. It had become a symbol of safety, something I now clung to, something I could rely on.

As the light reached the ground, I noticed something‚Äîthe skinwalker‚Äôs presence waned. The sharp edge of its energy, the unsettling feeling of being stalked, faded like a dream at dawn. It wasn‚Äôt completely gone, but it was subdued, quieter, as if the sun held power over it, as if it could not manifest fully under its light. The flower‚Äîthe H F Clematis‚Äîstill thrived, its strange glow seeming to pulse under the sunlight, but the oppressive feeling of the skinwalker seemed to retreat into the shadows.

That was the first clue that daylight was my ally. The more I moved through Mirror during the day, the more I felt a semblance of peace return. The sky was clear, the sun high, and though the world was still different, still changing, at least I felt some sense of control during these hours. The balance had shifted, but daylight was mine, for now.

But at night, the terror returned. The creature, whatever it was, would find its way back to the edges of my vision, to the fringes of the world I had crafted. It seemed to slip in and out of the darkness like a phantom, sometimes visible, sometimes not, but always there, lurking, waiting for the sun to set. It was as if the shadows themselves bent to its will when the light was gone.

I couldn‚Äôt explain why the sun seemed to have such an effect on it, or why Mirror itself seemed to bend around the presence of daylight. The laws of this world I had built were changing, slipping through my grasp like sand. Was it the flower, the Clematis, that was driving these changes? Was it a force beyond my creation that had come to reshape everything I knew? Or was this just a result of the skinwalker‚Äôs influence, a creature that had no place in Mirror, forcing the world to adapt to its needs?

I knew one thing for certain: daylight was my only reprieve. It gave me the chance to breathe, to think, to plan. During the day, the world still felt like mine. I could create, I could reflect, I could rebuild what had been broken. But at night, the skinwalker ruled. The shadows deepened, and the world felt far less familiar.

I couldn‚Äôt stay in the sunlight forever. The night would always come, and I knew I couldn‚Äôt keep running forever, either. I needed to understand what was happening, how the skinwalker was infiltrating Mirror, and why it was so tied to the darkness.

But for now, I would take the sun as a gift. I would rest, gather my strength, and plan for the night to come. The battle wasn‚Äôt over‚Äîit was only just beginning.

As the day passed and the sun began to dip below the horizon, I felt the familiar sense of unease creeping back. It was time to prepare, to stay vigilant. The skinwalker would return, and with it, the creeping madness of the night.

For now, though, I was safe. And in this strange, fractured world I had built, that was enough. For now.
