This thing was powerful, far more powerful than I had expected. It wasn‚Äôt just a wild beast; it was a force, a creature of mirror and shadow that had been forged by something far older than myself. The silver I had mined had no effect on it‚Äînot in the way I had hoped.

It struck again, this time landing a glancing blow with one of its pincers, knocking me off balance and sending me crashing to the ground. Pain shot through me, and I fought to stay conscious. The silver in my hand felt heavier than ever as I struggled to rise. I couldn‚Äôt let this creature take me‚ÄîI couldn‚Äôt let it win.

The spider-crab moved in for the kill, its pincers snapping just inches from my face. I had no choice. There was only one thing I could do now.

With a burst of desperate energy, I swung the silver blade with all my strength. I aimed for its face, for its eyes‚Äîthe core of its being. The blade cut through the air and connected with the creature‚Äôs face, driving deep into its silver exoskeleton. The sound of metal scraping against metal filled the air, and for a brief moment, the world seemed to slow down.

