But it wasn‚Äôt enough. The creature was still alive, and it was furious. It reared back, its pincers snapping violently as it prepared for another assault.

I had one more chance, one final chance to strike. I wasn‚Äôt going to let it take me. Not today.

I ducked low, dodging another swipe of its deadly claws. As the creature lunged forward again, I made my move. With a final burst of strength, I drove the silver blade into the creature‚Äôs underbelly, piercing through the soft spots in its armored shell.

It let out one final screech, a horrid, guttural cry, before its massive form collapsed to the ground, twitching in its death throes. The silver spider-crab fell silent.

I stood there, panting, my body trembling from exhaustion. I had survived, but just barely.

The battle had taken everything I had. And though I had won, I couldn‚Äôt shake the feeling that this was just one piece of a much larger, much darker puzzle. The skinwalkers, the Doppelvier‚Äîwhatever had brought the spider-crab to life, whatever force had been manipulating Mirror‚Äîwas still out there.

But for now, I had won. And as I stood over the defeated creature, I couldn‚Äôt help but wonder: what else would Mirror throw at me next?

There was no time to rest. The war was far from over.
