Chapter 20: Forging Silver: A Mirror Guide by Mira

The silver I had gathered from the giant spider-crab had changed everything. It wasn‚Äôt just a resource; it was the key to everything I had been working toward. As I stood before the piles of silver I had carefully harvested, a new feeling washed over me‚Äîpurpose. The battle against the skinwalkers, the Doppelvier, had escalated from survival to a war I was determined to win.

But to do that, I needed to forge the silver. I needed to craft weapons, tools, armor‚Äîanything that would help me survive this fight, anything that would give me the power to push back against the twisted creatures that had come to corrupt my world.

I had never forged silver before, but I knew how to work with materials in Mirror. I had created entire cities, gardens, and structures‚Äînow, I needed to apply that knowledge to something far more critical. I wasn‚Äôt just creating for beauty anymore. This was about strength, about defense, about survival.

Step 1: Preparing the Forge

I knew I couldn‚Äôt just create anything with the silver‚Äîthere was a process. The first step in forging silver was setting up the proper forge. Mirror wasn‚Äôt like the worlds I had once created‚Äîit didn‚Äôt have the same standard tools I was used to. So I had to make do, adapting the environment around me.

I started by gathering materials from the environment: stones, metals, and even the natural energy of Mirror itself. I found a flat surface in one of the caves, clearing away debris and creating a platform. Then, using some of the silver I had already gathered, I crafted a rudimentary furnace‚Äîa place to melt the silver down.

I built a fire inside the furnace using the natural wood and coal-like stones that were scattered throughout the cave. The flames flickered and crackled, but I could sense something more in the fire. It wasn‚Äôt just heat; it was energy. The energy of Mirror itself, responding to my will.

As the fire roared to life, I placed the silver chunks into the furnace, watching as they slowly began to melt, turning into a shimmering liquid that glowed with an eerie light. I could feel the silver pulse with a strange energy as it became malleable. The process wasn‚Äôt quick, but I knew it was necessary. The molten silver would need to cool, but before it did, I needed to shape it into something usable.

Step 2: Molding the Silver

Once the silver had melted into a liquid, I carefully poured it into a mold I had made from the hard stone around me. I was careful with every pour, ensuring that the silver would cool evenly, creating a solid form. The mold was simple‚Äîjust a long bar, but it would be enough to create the basic tools I needed.

I waited, feeling the heat of the molten silver still in the air. I knew it would take time for the silver to cool and solidify, but I couldn‚Äôt help but stare at it, fascinated by how it shifted and shimmered, like it was alive.

The time passed slowly, but eventually, the silver had cooled into solid bars. I could see the veins of pure silver, unmarred by corruption. The metal felt like it was pulsing with a life of its own, a power that wasn‚Äôt just physical‚Äîit was almost magical. I could feel the connection between the silver and the world around me, and I knew this wasn‚Äôt just any metal. This was special. This was the key to changing Mirror, to taking back control.

Step 3: Shaping the Silver into Weapons and Tools

With the silver now solidified, I could begin the real work‚Äîshaping it into tools, weapons, and armor.

The first task was creating a better weapon‚Äîone that could stand up to the skinwalkers‚Äô strange, otherworldly strength. I started with a sword. A long, gleaming blade that would cut through the shadowy forms of the Doppelvier with precision. The silver was still malleable enough that I could shape it, but I had to be careful, ensuring that the blade would be sharp and sturdy.

The process was slow, but I felt the satisfaction of creation in every strike. The silver blade took shape, its edge becoming razor-sharp, the hilt solidifying as I worked it into a simple yet effective design. As the blade began to take form, I could feel the weight of it in my hands, its balance perfect, its edge sharp enough to slice through the air with ease.

Next, I worked on armor. I wasn‚Äôt sure how long I would need to stay in Mirror‚Äôs dangerous depths, but I knew I needed protection if I were to face the Doppelvier again. I molded pieces of silver into lightweight, flexible armor‚Äîlight enough to move quickly in but strong enough to resist the skinwalkers' attacks. I layered the silver in thin sheets, ensuring each piece was molded to fit around my body, covering vital areas without sacrificing mobility.

And finally, I crafted a set of tools. Small, sharp implements made of silver, perfect for mining, carving, or‚Äîif necessary‚Äîdefending myself. They were not as refined as the weapons, but they were useful, and in Mirror, anything could be useful.

Step 4: Imbuing the Silver with Power

It wasn‚Äôt enough for the silver to just be functional. I needed to make it stronger, more than just a physical material. The creatures I faced weren‚Äôt just physical‚Äîthey were supernatural, their strength lying in their connection to the twisted energy of Mirror itself.

To combat that, I decided to imbue the silver with energy. I wasn‚Äôt sure how exactly, but I knew that silver could be more than just a weapon or a tool. It could be an extension of me, of my will.

I focused, channeling the energy of Mirror itself through the silver. I didn‚Äôt know if it would work, but I felt the heat from the forge grow stronger, pulsing in time with my thoughts. I reached out, using the molten silver to guide my will, feeling it bend, stretch, adapt as I infused it with the energy I had harnessed from the cave‚Äôs core.

The silver glowed, then faded, the power imbuing the metal with a quiet intensity. It wasn‚Äôt just a weapon anymore‚Äîit was an extension of my own being, shaped by my mind, my will, and the very energy of Mirror itself.

Step 5: Testing the Silver

I had done it. I had forged the silver into weapons, armor, and tools that could help me face the Doppelvier, but now I needed to test them.

I stepped outside the cave, feeling the weight of the sword at my side, the armor tight around my body. The night air was cool, and the quiet of Mirror seemed almost peaceful now. But I knew better. The skinwalkers could be anywhere. They were always watching, always waiting.

I swung the sword through the air, testing its balance, its sharpness. The blade cut through the air with ease, and I knew it was sharp enough to handle anything that might come my way. The armor fit comfortably, offering just the right amount of protection without feeling cumbersome. The tools were light, easy to maneuver, and well-made.

For the first time in a long while, I felt prepared. I felt like I had the power to face what was ahead.

But I also knew that this wasn‚Äôt over. The silver was my weapon, my ally, but the true fight was still out there, waiting for me.

Mirror had changed. I had changed. And now, it was time to take the next step in reclaiming my world.

The fight was just beginning.
