Chapter 26: Sun Trap (Mob Farm)

The war against the skinwalkers had evolved. What had begun as a straightforward battle for survival had transformed into something more strategic, a game of outsmarting an enemy that was capable of learning and adapting with each encounter. They no longer came in waves, charging recklessly toward my defenses. They moved in groups, small and calculated, always testing my limits.

But one thing they didn‚Äôt have was patience. They were relentless, yes, but not careful enough to avoid traps.

I needed to think outside the box. The towers, the LBRO, the Octagon Magic‚Äîthey had been effective, but the skinwalkers were adapting too quickly. I needed something that could deal with them at scale, something that would take their movements into account and maximize my own resources.

That‚Äôs when the idea hit me: a sun trap. A mob farm.

In Mirror, the creatures that wandered the world weren‚Äôt just flesh and bone. They were made of energy, shifting between forms and states. And as I watched the skinwalkers move in and out of the boundaries of my defenses, I realized that their ability to mimic and evade wasn‚Äôt just limited to how they looked‚Äîit extended to how they moved. They could evade the towers, slip through gaps in the LBRO, but they couldn‚Äôt avoid light.

Light was one of the most primal forces in Mirror. It was part of the world‚Äôs creation, part of its fundamental structure. The sun was a source of power, of energy, and the skinwalkers‚Äîthe Doppelvier‚Äîwere creatures of darkness. They avoided the light, hid from it, and relied on shadows to move undetected.

What if I could trap them in the light? What if I could make the sun itself a weapon?

Step 1: Constructing the Trap

I knew the basics of farming in Mirror. I had cultivated crops, mined resources, and even designed automatic systems to harvest materials. But this wasn‚Äôt about crops or resources‚Äîit was about control.

The concept was simple: create a space where skinwalkers couldn‚Äôt escape, where they would be drawn into the light, and then make sure they couldn‚Äôt leave.

I began by selecting a location. A wide, open space outside the LBRO, where the light could reach the farthest corners of the area. I needed an expansive, unobstructed spot, and Mirror‚Äôs plains offered the perfect setting.

Next, I designed the trap. The idea was to create an enclosed area where sunlight would shine directly on the ground at specific times of the day. The skinwalkers would be drawn to this light, thinking they could use it as a path to escape‚Äîor perhaps they wouldn‚Äôt be able to resist its allure. Either way, they would end up trapped in it.

I began by digging a series of trenches, carving out a large rectangular area in the middle of the open plain. The trench walls were high enough to trap anything that fell in, yet not so high that they couldn‚Äôt be scaled. I filled the trench with sharp, silver-tipped stakes, designed to pierce the skinwalkers' forms if they tried to climb over the walls.

The most important part, however, was the lighting. I created a series of reflective surfaces‚Äîhuge mirrors, angled at precisely the right direction, that would channel the sun‚Äôs light directly into the trench at the right times. These mirrors would harness the sun's energy, focusing it into a concentrated beam of light that would shine directly into the trench during the day, especially when the sun was at its highest. The light would create an intense glare, blinding and disorienting, and the skinwalkers would be compelled to move into it, thinking they could use the light as an escape route.

I placed additional traps around the perimeter, designed to funnel anything that ventured too close into the light-filled trench. The goal was simple: get the skinwalkers to fall into the trap, and once they were in, they would be stuck.

Step 2: Testing the Farm

With the trap built, the next task was to see if it worked. I didn‚Äôt want to wait until the skinwalkers themselves had wandered into the trap, so I decided to test it with a few smaller creatures first.

I went out into the wilderness of Mirror, finding the various hostile creatures that roamed the land. I knew they weren‚Äôt as clever as the skinwalkers, but they were still unpredictable. I led a few toward the sun trap, watching from a distance as they neared the reflective beams of light.

The moment they crossed into the range of the mirrors, the creatures seemed to slow, confused by the intense brightness. The light acted like a magnet, drawing them into the trench. Some tried to run back into the shadows, but the mirrors redirected the sunlight, pushing them forward. And when they did finally fall into the trench, they were immediately trapped, caught on the silver-tipped stakes at the bottom. The light made it impossible for them to escape‚Äîthere was nowhere to hide.

It was working.

I repeated the process, testing it again and again with different creatures, ensuring that everything was functioning as planned. The traps were holding, the sunlight was powerful enough to draw the creatures in, and once they were inside the trench, they were effectively neutralized.

But the real test would come when the skinwalkers arrived. I could feel it. They were watching me, waiting for me to slip up, to let my guard down.

Step 3: Skinwalkers Fall Into the Trap

The day came sooner than I expected. I had been observing the movement of the skinwalkers from the edges of Mirror, watching them slip through cracks in the LBRO and move in their small groups. But now, they were more focused‚Äîmore deliberate.

They had been probing the defenses, looking for a way in. I could feel them approaching. They were closing in on the sun trap.

I waited in the shadows, my silver sword at my side. I had a front-row seat to the most dangerous game of cat and mouse I had ever played.

I saw them‚Äîthree of them‚Äîmoving cautiously toward the edge of the trap, their forms flickering in and out of the shadows. They hadn‚Äôt seen it yet. They hadn‚Äôt realized they were being herded into the trap. I could feel their presence, their curiosity, as they moved toward the light.

The first skinwalker stepped into the field of light.

It paused, its form flickering in the brightness, but something was pulling it forward. The mirrors‚Äô energy, the concentrated sunlight, made it almost impossible for the skinwalker to resist. The others followed, drawn into the beam of light, their twisted bodies moving toward the shining beacon.

I watched with a quiet sense of satisfaction as the first skinwalker stumbled into the trench, followed by the second. The third one hesitated, but not for long. It too, unable to resist the pull of the light, fell into the trap.

They were stuck. The stakes in the trench caught them, and no matter how hard they tried, they couldn‚Äôt escape. The blinding sunlight kept them disoriented, unable to fight back.

I stepped forward, watching them struggle. They had fallen right into my trap. And this time, I wasn‚Äôt just surviving‚ÄîI was winning. The sun trap was more than just a defense. It was a powerful countermeasure, a way to force the skinwalkers into submission.

I knew there would be more. There would always be more skinwalkers testing, probing, seeking a way to infiltrate Mirror. But now I had something new in my arsenal‚Äîsomething that would make them think twice before trying again.

And as I stood over the fallen skinwalkers, their mimicry broken and powerless in the glare of the sun, I realized that I had control again. I had turned the tables. Mirror was no longer just a place to hide from the darkness. It was mine to protect‚Äîand mine to defend.

The fight wasn‚Äôt over.

But for now, I had won again.
