Chapter 64: Crab Style (Advanced Waterbending)

The world of Mirror had changed in ways I couldn‚Äôt have predicted. Every step I took into the unknown, every lesson I learned from the forces around me, shifted the foundation of what I understood. And after the encounter with the lobster, I thought I had grasped the full range of waterbending‚Äôs potential. I thought I had mastered its flow‚Äîits dance between creation and destruction.

But then, the crab came.

The crab had shown me something beyond mere flow‚Äîit had taught me the art of resistance, of stability, of holding fast in the face of overwhelming forces. The essence of the crab wasn‚Äôt just about opposition‚Äîit was about balance, about finding strength not in bending to the world‚Äôs currents, but in standing firm against them when necessary. The lobster had been fluid, chaotic, a force of raw potential. The crab, by contrast, was structured, grounded, the embodiment of defense.

What I realized was that Crab Style wasn‚Äôt just about waterbending in the traditional sense. It was about learning to channel the inherent stillness and strength of resistance into the fluidity of water. It was about combining the energy of creation with the steadfastness of defense.

And so, I began the next phase of my training.
Step 1: The Principles of Crab Style

Crab Style wasn‚Äôt simply a technique; it was a philosophy. The lobster had taught me the power of fluidity, the importance of moving with the current, but the crab offered a new lesson: resistance, control, and the strength of standing firm. In Crab Style, water wasn‚Äôt simply bent through force. It was bent through understanding and holding onto one‚Äôs foundation‚Äîjust like the crab holding its ground against a storm.

In this form of advanced waterbending, I had to combine both the chaos of creation with the stability of resistance. The water needed to be allowed to flow, but it needed to be controlled‚Äînot through suppression, but through structure. It wasn‚Äôt about making the water bend to me; it was about shaping its natural path, allowing it to move but within the boundaries I set.

The first principle of Crab Style was the foundation. Just as a crab‚Äôs shell is its source of strength, so too must the bender's foundation be strong‚Äîrooted in both inner peace and external stability.

The second principle was resilience. Water, when resisted, could become a force of immense pressure‚Äîyet it could also bend in a way that gave it both the power to crush and the grace to heal. Resilience was the heart of Crab Style. Water should not be feared when it moves violently, for it is merely a reflection of natural force. It should be directed, guided, shaped‚Äîwithout breaking its essence.
Step 2: The First Lesson ‚Äì Holding Firm

Aemily and I stood at the edge of New Mirror City, overlooking the vast expanse of water that stretched beyond the horizon. The city‚Äôs canals had always been a place of tranquility, a place where the gentle flow of water represented peace and harmony. But now, with my new understanding of Crab Style, I realized the canals could be more than peaceful‚Äîthey could be powerful.

I closed my eyes and focused, drawing upon the stillness of the earth beneath me. With one deep breath, I imagined my energy grounding itself deep into the water beneath me, solidifying it in place, like the foundation of the crab's shell. The water responded slowly at first, rippling as if unsure of my intent.

I raised my hands, and the water rose up, forming an arch before me. But unlike the smooth, fluid movements of the past, I shaped the water with structure, with intention. It was still flowing, still alive, but it no longer moved freely. It bent to my will‚Äîgently, but with purpose. I was grounding it, stabilizing it, keeping it strong.

Aemily watched closely. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs not just about holding the water in place,‚Äù she said, intrigued. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre using the water‚Äôs natural flow, but you‚Äôre controlling it, shaping it from within.‚Äù

I nodded. ‚ÄúExactly. Crab Style is about resisting the chaos. It‚Äôs about maintaining control, but not in the way I used to. It‚Äôs not about stopping the water‚Äîit‚Äôs about guiding it, holding it when necessary.‚Äù

The water arched higher, twisting into a barrier. It wasn‚Äôt perfect‚Äîit wavered slightly, struggling against the pressure I applied. But with each passing moment, I felt the strength grow within me. I wasn‚Äôt forcing the water to obey. I was standing firm, creating space for the water to exist without losing its essence.
Step 3: The Claws of Water ‚Äì Destruction and Creation in Harmony

Once I had mastered holding water in place, it was time to learn how to use it in action. I had to embrace the duality of Crab Style‚Äîthe way the crab could be both defensive and offensive. The crab‚Äôs claws were weapons, powerful tools of both creation and destruction. Likewise, water could both nurture and destroy, depending on how it was shaped.

I imagined the water, as I had before, rising from the canals. This time, instead of simply holding it in place, I directed it with precision, using my understanding of resistance to shape it into something more aggressive‚Äîsomething that could defend but also strike.

I focused my will, and the water coiled like a serpent, twisting itself into two large, sharp tendrils. The water was still fluid, still alive, but it had taken a new form‚Äîone that could attack. The tendrils rose into the air, snapping like claws, ready to strike.

Aemily took a step back. ‚ÄúSo it‚Äôs not just about standing firm anymore. You can attack with it.‚Äù

I grinned, feeling the power of the water surge through me. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs about using the resistance of water to create force, to strike. Just as the crab uses its claws to defend and attack, I can use the water‚Äôs natural flow to create both destruction and protection.‚Äù

I directed the tendrils, crashing them against the stone walls of the city‚Äôs edge. The force of the water hit with the power of a crashing wave, but it didn‚Äôt shatter. Instead, it bent the stone, leaving deep marks but not breaking it completely. It was precise, controlled, and deeply powerful.
Step 4: The Dance of Creation and Destruction

In the following days, I continued to refine my mastery of Crab Style. It was a dance of creation and destruction‚Äîmoving between gentle flow and powerful force, grounding the water while still giving it the freedom to move. I learned to bend water into shields, into claws, into waves of pressure that could both protect and demolish.

Aemily often joined me in these exercises, learning Crab Style alongside me. Together, we practiced in the canals, shaping the water into barriers, creating weapons, and finding new ways to use the water‚Äôs force.

