I reached out and touched the cover of the book, my fingers brushing the worn leather. As soon as my hand made contact, a surge of energy passed through me‚Äîsubtle but undeniable. The book was alive, not in the way that a living being is, but in the sense that it held knowledge, power, and purpose that extended beyond its physical form.

Ham seemed to sense the shift as well. ‚ÄúI was supposed to help guide humanity through the flood,‚Äù he said, his voice filled with an unspoken depth. ‚ÄúTo protect the ark and carry its passengers to safety. But I failed. And now... now I see. The Bible is more than just a story. It‚Äôs a map. A guide.‚Äù

I opened the book, and my eyes fell on the first page. The words were ancient, written in a language that I almost understood. The Book of Genesis. The story of creation. The beginning of everything. I felt a pull, a connection to those words, as if they held a key to understanding not just Ham‚Äôs past, but my own place in the world.

‚ÄúThe beginning of everything‚Ä¶‚Äù I whispered.

Ham nodded, his eyes locked on the pages as if the words were speaking directly to him. ‚ÄúThe Bible doesn‚Äôt just tell stories. It guides us. It teaches us what we were meant to be. It shows us our origins, our purpose. And even when we fail‚Äîwhen we think we are lost‚Äîthere is always a way back.‚Äù
Step 3: The Flood and the Ark

