I pressed my hands to my face, trying to ground myself, but the sensation of d√©j√† vu was overwhelming. This was a dream, wasn‚Äôt it? A false awakening. The worst kind of dream‚Äîthe one where you think you‚Äôve woken up, but you haven‚Äôt.
Step 3: The Search for an Answer

I had to know. I couldn‚Äôt remain trapped in this false cycle forever. The urge to break free consumed me. I needed to wake up, to find the truth.

I rushed to the door, but as soon as my hand touched the handle, I was back in the same room. The same sterile environment. The same disquieting sense of wrongness. I turned, breathing heavily, trying to calm myself, but the room was shifting, altering with each breath. The walls pulsed. The floor became spongy, as though the world was breathing in sync with me, alive but unstable.

What is this place? I asked myself. Was it the dream? Or had it already been the waking world?

I slammed my fist against the wall, my knuckles throbbing from the impact. The sound reverberated through the room, but the walls didn‚Äôt crack. They didn‚Äôt even respond. It was as if everything around me was an illusion, carefully crafted to keep me in this loop, to prevent me from waking up‚Äîor maybe, to make me question whether I was ever awake at all.
Step 4: The Moment of Clarity

